Families and communities across our country suffer immeasurable pain from the loss of loved ones due to suicide; the tenth leading cause of death in our country.

We must raise awareness of mental health and suicide prevention. If you are in need of support, please call the 24-hour National Suicide Prevention Lifeline at 1-800-273-8255. Remember, there is help and hope for a better tomorrow. #WorldSuicidePreventionDay

Lt. Governor Jacqueline Coleman
September 4 at 6:09 PM ·

In these unprecedented times every story of triumph can inspire hope. On behalf Team Kentucky, I want to extend our congratulations to Shedaresthedevil, Florent Geroux, Flurry Racing Stable, Qatar Racing Stable & Big Aut Farms and Brad Cox on winning the 146th running of the Kentucky Oaks. Your accomplishment today will forever be a part of the history of this great American sporting event!

Today the Voting Rights Act marks 55 years and we still have work to do. From my executive order on restoring voting rights to non-violent felons, to working towards expanded voting hours and access, this administration is dedicated to creating a more just and equitable commonwealth.

Visit Elect.Ky.Gov to register to vote here in Kentucky. If you are a Kentuckian previously denied the right to vote, visit CivilRightsRestoration.ky.gov, a website we announced on March 4, the day this photo was taken, to check eligibility. #TeamKentucky
text:

post_text:
We are instituting 3 major changes to improve the unemployment claims processing system.

1. Reorganizing the unemployment office and moving it to the Labor Cabinet.

2. Contracting with an outside vendor to train more claim processors, answer more public questions and fix the system.

3. Adding more in-person services, including out in the counties.
text:
We are instituting 3 major changes to improve the unemployment claims processing system.

1. Reorganizing the unemployment office and moving it to the Labor Cabinet.

2. Contracting with an outside vendor to train more claim processors, answer more public questions and fix the system.

3. Adding more in-person services, including out in the counties.

KCC.KY.GOV
Welcome

For the first time ever we've allowed mail in voting and no excuse early voting. In addition, 175,053 ex-offenders have had their voting rights restored.

As of 4 p.m. June 1, Gov. Beshear said there were at least 10,046 #COVID19 cases in Kentucky. Read more: https://go.usa.gov/xwbwu

Monday morning Gov. Beshear addressed recent events in Louisville, and joined Breonna Taylor's mother, Tamika Palmer, along with attorney Lonita Baker, to speak on the search for justice. View the news conference: https://bit.ly/2XTJHZF
